e value of each substring is less than or equal to k.\n\nReturn the minimum number of substrings in a good partition of s. If no good partition of s exists, return -1.\nNote that:\n\nThe value of a string is its result when interpreted as an integer. For example, the value of \"123\" is 123 and the value of \"1\" is 1.\nA substring is a contiguous sequence of characters within a string.\n\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: s = \"165462\", k = 60\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: We can partition the string into substrings \"16\", \"54\", \"6\", and \"2\". Each substring has a value less than or equal to k = 60.\nIt can be shown that we cannot partition the string into less than 4 substrings.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: s = \"238182\", k = 5\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: There is no good partition for this string.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= s.length <= 105\ns[i] is a digit from '1' to '9'.\n1 <= k <= 109\n\n \n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumPartition(self, s: str, k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumPartition(self, s: str, k: int) -> int:\n        # Initialize the number of partitions to 0\n        partitions = 0\n        # Initialize the current number as an empty string\n        current_number = \"\"\n        \n        for digit in s:\n            # Try to add the current digit to the current number\n            if int(current_number + digit) <= k:\n                current_number += digit\n            else:\n                # If adding the digit makes the number greater than k,\n                # we need to start a new partition\n                partitions += 1\n                current_number = digit\n            \n            # If at any point a single digit is greater than k, return -1\n            if int(digit) > k:\n                return -1\n        \n        # If there's any remaining number, it counts as a partition\n        if current_number:\n            partitions += 1\n        \n        return partitions\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through each digit in the string `s` and tries to build the largest possible substring that is less than or equal to `k`. If adding the next digit would make the substring larger than `k`, it starts a new partition. If a single digit is larger than `k`, it returns `-1` as no valid partitioning is possible. Finally, it returns the total number of partitions needed.", "estimated_date": 1672531200000}